soilPb.units: mg / kg; 4 M HNO3-extractable (i.e., total) concentrations.  In a survey of long-term studies in the United Kingdom, Sweden, Germany, and the U.S., McGrath et al. (1995) reported that the minimum total soil concentrations that negatively affected soil microbial biomass ranged from 180 to 857 mg Zn kg-1, 0.7 to 6.0 mg Cd kg-1, 70 to 384 mg Cu kg-1, 22 to 35 mg Ni kg-1, 40 to 114 mg Pb kg-1, and 85 to 105 mg Cr kg-1. Only the 4 M HNO3 soil Cd concentrations (measure of total content) in our grassland biosolids treatment fell within this range (Table 3). All other soil trace-metal levels at our grassland site were below ranges reported by McGrath et al. (1995), indicating that biosolids-borne trace metals probably did not determinately affect actively metabolizing biomass.
